Here is the code in C# that outputs the unclosed brackets in the given string:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string s = "(){}[])))(((()))[][][]{}{}{}{()(){}}{}{([][{)})"; // the given string

        Stack<int> stack = new Stack<int>();
        for (int i = 0; i < s.Length; i++)
        {
            char c = s[i];
            if (c == '(' || c == '{' || c == '[')
            {
                stack.Push(i);
            }
            else if (c == ')' || c == '}' || c == ']')
            {
                if (stack.Count == 0)
                {
                    Console.WriteLine("Unexpected closing bracket at position " + i);
                }
                else
                {
                    int start = stack.Pop();
                    if (c == ')' && s[start] != '(' ||
                        c == '}' && s[start] != '{' ||
                        c == ']' && s[start] != '[')
                    {
                        Console.WriteLine("Mismatched brackets at positions " + start + " and " + i);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        while (stack.Count > 0)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Unclosed bracket at position " + stack.Pop());
        }
    }
}
```

This program uses a stack to keep track of the positions of opening brackets. When a closing bracket is encountered, it pops the last position from the stack and checks if the brackets match. If there is a mismatch, it reports the positions of the mismatched brackets. If there are still brackets on the stack after iterating through the string, it reports their positions as unclosed brackets.

